<!-- info_hardpoint needs a special class I think -->
<!-- NOTE: select a model from: models/communication/terminal_com_station*.mdl for r1 model -->
<!-- or models/robots/mobile_hardpoint/mobile_hardpoint.mdl for r2 model -->
<!-- TODO:
    gamemode_at, cp, ffa, lh, sur, tday
    hardpointFrontlineOverride, Yaw
    hardpointName
    nearTarget
    target
    triggerTarget
-->
<point name="info_hardpoint" color=".3 .3 1" box="-64 -64 0 64 64 72" model="models/robots/mobile_hardpoint/mobile_hardpoint.obj">
Used to spawn the hardpoints in hardpoint domination.
-------- KEYS --------
<integer key="teamnum" name="Team number" value="-1">TEAM_ANY = -1; TEAM_BOTH = 4; TEAM_MILITIA = 3, TEAM_IMC = 2</integer>
<targetname key="targetname" name="Target Name" value="hardpoint_">UNIQUE Target name</targetname>
<angles key="angles" name="Pitch Yaw Roll" value="0 0 0">Individual control of PITCH, YAW, and ROLL.</angles>
<string key="hardpointGroup" name="Hardpoint Group" value="A">Used to indicate the hardpoint name (A,B,C)</string>
<real key="scale" name="Scale" value="1">Value used to scale the ents model, hitboxes DO NOT scale.</real>
-------- NOTES --------
Model must be set, and it can be anything
</point>

<point name="info_frontline" color=".3 .3 1" box="-8 -8 -8 8 8 8">
Used to indicate the "frontlines" to NPCs (where they should go and shoot at eachother)
-------- KEYS --------
<integer key="teamnum" name="Team number" value="-1">TEAM_ANY = -1; TEAM_BOTH = 4; TEAM_MILITIA = 3, TEAM_IMC = 2</integer>
<targetname key="targetname" name="Target Name" value="frontline_">UNIQUE Target name</targetname>
<angles key="angles" name="Pitch Yaw Roll" value="0 0 0">Individual control of PITCH, YAW, and ROLL.</angles>
<string key="group" name="Group" value="Hangar">Used to indicate which frontlines are linked together.</string>
<real key="scale" name="Scale" value="1">Value used to scale the ents model, hitboxes DO NOT scale.</real>
<boolean key="spectrepoint" name="Spectre Point" value="0">Used to indicate whether only Spectres should use this frontline entity. These should be used in combination with regular frontlines.</boolean>
<boolean key="gamemode_at" name="gamemode_at" value="0">Use this for Attrition?</boolean>
<boolean key="gamemode_cp" name="gamemode_cp" value="0">Use this for Hardpoint domination?</boolean>
<boolean key="gamemode_ctf" name="gamemode_ctf" value="0">Use this for Capture the flag?</boolean>
<boolean key="gamemode_ctfp" name="gamemode_ctfp" value="0">Use this for Capture the flag pro?</boolean>
<boolean key="gamemode_mfd" name="gamemode_mfd" value="0">Use this for Marked for death?</boolean>
<boolean key="gamemode_mfdp" name="gamemode_mfdp" value="0">Use this for Marked for death pro?</boolean>
<boolean key="gamemode_lts" name="gamemode_lts" value="0">Use this for Last Titan standing?</boolean>
<boolean key="gamemode_wlts" name="gamemode_wlts" value="0">Use this for Wingman LTS?</boolean>
<boolean key="gamemode_ps" name="gamemode_ps" value="0">Use this for Pilot skirmish?</boolean>
<boolean key="gamemode_tdm" name="gamemode_tdm" value="0">Use this for Pilot hunter?</boolean>
<boolean key="gamemode_ffa" name="gamemode_ffa" value="0">Use this for Free for all?</boolean>
<boolean key="gamemode_scv" name="gamemode_scv" value="0">Use this for Scavenger?</boolean>
-------- NOTES --------
Enough player and NPC deaths for a specific team will make the frontlines fall back for that team
Should be used to divide the map in straight lines, with each line corresponding to a team
So, for example, the left side of a map (near the starting milita spawn) should be ONLY militia info_frontlines
And the right side, should be ONLY IMC info_frontlines
Make sure to set each of the info_frontlines in the same line to the same group
</point>

<!--
=============================================================================
 ZIPLINE
=============================================================================
-->

<!-- TODO: model="models/editor/axis_helper_thick.mdl" -->
<point name="move_rope" color=".3 .3 1" box="-8 -8 -8 8 8 8">
-------- KEYS --------
<targetname key="targetname" name="Target Name" value="zipline_">The target name of the zipline</targetname>
<targetname key="NextKey" name="Next Key" value="zipline_">The second point of the zipline</targetname>
<boolean key="Zipline" name="Zipline">Set this to 1</boolean>
<integer key="Subdiv" name="Subdivisions" value="0">Number of subdivisions between each rope segment. Higher values make smoother ropes, but are slower to render.</integer>
<integer key="Slack" name="Slack">How much extra length the rope has (by default it has the length between its two endpoints in the editor).</integer>
<integer key="MoveSpeed" name="Move Speed" value="64">Move Speed</integer>
-------- NOTES --------
You can also use move_rope and keyframe_rope to make decorative cables
Titanfall ziplines use a generic texture, unlike the Yellow texture used in Apex
Source Engine guides recommend using one move_rope then a series of keyframe_rope for each key
IIRC move_rope ends can be used to create loose cable ends
</point>

